Effects of Employment Rate on the US Dollar¶

Spring 2024 Data Science Project

Author: Benard Wangombe Kihiuria

Introduction: This study was conducted to find out whether or not we can use fundamental analysis (formal analysis technique that takes into consideration variables such as news, interest rates, etc.) in the form of analyzing unemployment rates, to determine whether or not to buy a currency. The goal is to potentially find a correlation between US unemployment rate and current conversion rates and be able to predict what the price should be based off of the unemployment report. Confirmation that there is a correlation between unemployment and the conversion rate would then allow someone to be able to predict what the conversion rate should theoretically be, and decide to buy or sell their currency. Answering these questions would be important as it would allow traders to have more information at their fingertips that they could use to make better and more informed decisions.

Part 0: Background Knowledge¶

What is Forex?¶

Definition : Forex (FX) refers to the global electronic marketplace for trading international currencies and currency derivatives. It has no central physical location, yet the forex market is the largest, most liquid market in the world by trading volume, with trillions of dollars changing hands every day. Most of the trading is done through banks, brokers, and financial institutions.

This is the same market that the US Dollar is traded on with institutions buying and selling the currency that they believe is going to increase in price.

How Pairs Are Organized¶

For currency pairs it is necessary to buy a currency in reference to another currency. There is a standardized way that they are organized to know which currency you are expecting to rise or fall. For example let us reference the currency pair USD/JPY. In these cases the first currency listed (USD) is considered the base currency and the second currency (JPY) is considered the quote currency

What do Base and Quote Currencies Even Mean?¶

What you are analyzing when you look at a price in reference to base and quote currencies is essentially what the base currency is worth in context to the quote currency. In other words how much of the quote currency will you receive for one unit of the base currency. With in the case of USD/JPY which currently has a value of 151.36. This means that for 1 US Dollar you will receive 151.36 Japanese Yen.

How to Determine the Weakness and Strength of a Currency?¶

With this in hand we are able to understand that when a base currency has a strong economy then it will be worth more in the quote currency, and the opposite being true in when the economy of the base currency is weak it will be worth less in the quote currency.

How to Make Profit?¶

Using this forex traders are able to make profits on the rise and fall of a currency. Where if you believe that the currency is going to fall in reference to the quote currency you buy alot of the quote currency and when it reaches your profit point you buy the base currency back with the quote currency you bought initially. And vice versa if you believe it is going to rise you buy alot of the base currency and when it is worth more in the quote currency then you exchange it for a profit.

Task 4.4 : Hypothesis Test

Null Hypothesis H0: There is no relationship between unemployment rate and currency pairs
Alternative Hypothesis H1: There is a relationship between unemployment rate and currency pairs
Significance Rate = 0.05

First to check this we want to use a chi squared test and to do that we need to categorically regard the data as whether or not it is greater than the mean of each respective pair so we are going to create a new column adressing that fact for every single pair and store it in a temp_df variable.

We also want to merge our temporary dataframe with the respective unemployment rate

In [17]:
# Instantiate pairs for simpler iteration
pairs = ["GBP/USD", 'EUR/USD', 'AUD/USD' , 'USD/JPY', 'USD/CHF']
In [18]:
# Function that will be run on each column regarding whether or not the current currency rate is higher than the mean given its unemployment rate
def is_greater_than_mean(x, mean):
    if x >= mean: 
        return 'No'
    else :
        return 'Yes'

# Create a temp_df we can use and modify freely
temp_df = df
temp_df = temp_df[temp_df["Date"].dt.day == 1]
temp_df = pd.merge(temp_df, unemployment_df)

# Creating the new columns
for i in pairs:
    try:
        temp_df[f"Greater Than Mean: {i}"] = temp_df[i].apply(lambda x: is_greater_than_mean(x, df[i].describe()['mean']))
    except Exception:
        continue

In [20]:
# Finds the p value for each pair and plots the relationship between unemployment and mean level
for i in pairs:
    # Limiting for more common sample size
    temp_df = temp_df[temp_df['Unemployment Rate'] <= 5]

    # Find important columns
    a = temp_df[f'Greater Than Mean: {i}']
    b = temp_df['Unemployment Rate']

    # Creation of the contingency table
    table = pd.crosstab(a, b, rownames=[''], colnames=['Unemployment Rate']) 
    
    # Plot the relationship between the two columns
    table.plot(kind='bar')
    plt.title(f'Relationship Between Unemployment Rate and Mean Level for {i}')
    plt.xlabel('Greater Than Mean')
    plt.ylabel('Count of Times Greater than Mean')
    plt.legend(loc='center')
    
    # Extract the p-value from the contingency table and print it out
    print(f'P-Value for {i} = {scipy.stats.chi2_contingency(table).pvalue}')

P-Value for GBP/USD = 0.0020695437403777115
P-Value for EUR/USD = 0.00044713207193868124
P-Value for AUD/USD = 0.0022100141577719983
P-Value for USD/JPY = 0.06859729568406199
P-Value for USD/CHF = 0.12016970806401533

As you can see from the p values for USD/JPY and USD/CHF we saw p values greater than our level of significance and for the other currencies we saw p values less than our level of significance. Therefore in the case of the p values less than our level of significance we will reject our Null hypothesis and understand that unemployment rate does have an effect on our currency rate and we can say the opposite and accept our null hypothesis in the case of USD/CHF and USD/JPY as they had a p value greater than our significance level stated above.

Task 5.2: For this we want to implement a regression model for our seemingly linear dataset to predict conversion rates based off unemployment in the United States.

In [24]:
# Function to get the error rate for the model we create for a specific pair with the ability to plot it as well
def get_error_rates(pair, plot=True):
    # We first want to split the different datasets into train and test
    X_linear, Y_linear = df["Unemployment Rate"], df[pair]
    X_linear_train, X_linear_test, Y_linear_train, Y_linear_test = train_test_split(X_linear, Y_linear)

    # We do this to turn the series that we obtain into a dataframe
    X_linear_train = X_linear_train.to_frame()
    X_linear_test = X_linear_test.to_frame()

    # We fit the model to be able to work under polynomial features so that we can have a different degree that more aptly fits what we are looking for
    polyFeatures = PolynomialFeatures(degree=5, include_bias=False)
    xPolyTrain = polyFeatures.fit_transform(X_linear_train)
    xPolyTest = polyFeatures.fit_transform(X_linear_test)
    
    polyModelTrain = LinearRegression()
    polyModelTrain.fit(xPolyTrain, Y_linear_train)

    # This is the prediction that we get when testing the feature values in regard to the model that we created earlier
    Y_linear_test_pred = polyModelTrain.predict(polyFeatures.fit_transform(X_linear_test.values))
    
    # Calculate MSE and R^2
    mse_linear_test = mean_squared_error(Y_linear_test, Y_linear_test_pred)
    r2_linear_test = r2_score(Y_linear_test, Y_linear_test_pred)
   
    # This is simply in regards to whether or not you want to plot the regression line and the scatter plot with the train and test data highlighted
    if plot :
        xDeltaTrain = np.linspace(X_linear_train.min(), X_linear_train.max(), 1000)
        yDeltaTrain = polyModelTrain.predict(polyFeatures.fit_transform(xDeltaTrain.reshape(-1, 1)))
        
        # Graph the quadratic regression
        train_data = plt.scatter(X_linear_train, Y_linear_train, color='cyan')
        test_data = plt.scatter(X_linear_test, Y_linear_test, color='red')
        train_data.set_label('Train Data')
        test_data.set_label('Test Data')

       
        plt.plot(xDeltaTrain, yDeltaTrain, color='orange', linewidth=2, label='Regression Line')
        plt.legend(loc="upper right")
        plt.xlabel('Unemployment Rate', fontsize=10)
        plt.ylabel('Conversion Rate', fontsize=10)
        plt.title(f'Relation of Unemployment Rate and Conversion Rate for {pair}', fontsize=10)
    
        plt.show()

    # Return the MSE and R2 score in terms of a tuple
    return mse_linear_test, r2_linear_test

Task 5.3: Now that we have a way to plot and analyze our regression model I think it would be interesting to figure out the average MSE score and R2 score given different splits and their corresponding line of best fit in addition to how that relates for every individual pair.

In [25]:
iterations = 100
average_mse = 0
average_r2 = 0

# We want to find the average MSE and R2 score for each pair and we do this by iteratively getting the current MSE and R2 and then dividing it by the number of iterations chosen.
for i in pairs:
    for j in range(iterations):
        curr_mse, curr_r2 = get_error_rates(i, plot=False)
        
        average_mse += curr_mse
        average_r2 += curr_r2
    
    print(f"Information Regarding {i}\n-----------------------------\nThe average MSE is {average_mse/iterations}\nThe average R2 score is {average_r2/iterations}\n")
    average_mse, average_r2 = 0, 0

Part 7: Insights and Conclusions¶

I hope that you as a reader was able to not only learn more about forex but how important it is in our daily lives. How in some cases unemployment can be a good indicator on what a conversion rate can be and the parts that it has its own flaws. As we can see from our predictions in most cases on average we are not able to reach a suitable percentage to have meaningingful insight that is gained. It should be stated that the correlation actually has to be really high especially in the case with forex pairs. When they are assessed they are often to the 4th decimal place, for example 1.4000. And it should be noted that a movement from 1.4000 to 1.4001 would actually have to some importance as forex pairs are heavily leveraged in some cases meaning that such a simple move could cost millions of losses depending on the position. So with such a low r2 score we have to tread very carefully. In addition to this we can see from the data that unemployment rate doesn't give us enough information. For example lets look at USD/CHF, we have the same conversion when the unemployment rate was 3.5 as it was when it was 5.0. There also seems to be a vertical line almost at the 3.5 unemployment rate that well represents the data to so our regression line isn't able to account for the variance. In this case we even received a negative R2 score in one cycle which is honestly unnaceptable in the context of making a profit. It was interesting confirming that one feature certainly isn't enough and I would definitely have fun maybe making this more dimensional in the future and learn more. I plan to study more about the intersection between finance and computer science and hope to take you all on the ride with me.
